synth_data:
World War II began with the invasion of Poland by Nazi Germany. The roots of the conflict, however, lay in the complex web of alliances, treaties, and historical grievances following World War I and the global economic turmoil of the 1920s and 1930s.

The Treaty of Versailles, which concluded World War I, imposed heavy reparations and territorial losses on Germany. This created a sense of humiliation and resentment among the German people. The economic hardships of the Great Depression further destabilized the country, creating fertile ground for the rise of Adolf Hitler and his National Socialist (Nazi) Party.

Hitler, who became Chancellor of Germany in 1933, pursued aggressive territorial expansion. He aimed to unite all ethnic Germans into one nation and create more "living space" (Lebensraum) for the German people, which he sought to achieve through the conquest of neighboring countries.

In the years leading up to the war, Hitler violated the Treaty of Versailles by rearming Germany

synth_data:
World War II began with the invasion of Poland by Nazi Germany. The key events leading up to the start of the war include:

1. Treaty of Versailles (1919): The harsh terms imposed on Germany after its defeat in World War I created widespread resentment and economic hardship, which Adolf Hitler exploited to rise to power.

2. Rise of Totalitarian Regimes: In the 1920s and 1930s, totalitarian regimes took control in Germany (under Hitler), Italy (under Benito Mussolini), and Japan, all of which harbored expansionist ambitions.

3. Expansionist Policies: Germany and Italy, under fascist leadership, and Japan, under militarist influence, sought to expand their territories. Germany remilitarized the Rhineland in 1936, annexed Austria in 1938 (Anschluss), and seized the Sudetenland from Czechoslovakia in 1938 following the Munich Agreement.

4. Failure of Appeasement: European
